The '''Kudurru for Šitti-Marduk''' is a white limestone boundary stone ([[Kudurru]]) of [[Nebuchadrezzar I]], a king of the 2nd Dynasty of [[Isin]], ca. the late 12th century BC. He is known to have made at least four kudurru boundary stones.
Some kudurrus are known for their representations of the king, etc, who conscripted the stones production. Most kudurrus are attested by honored gods of [[Mesopotamia]] and are often displayed graphically in segmented [[Register (sculpture)|register]]s on the stone.
The obverse of the ''Kudurru for Šitti-Marduk'' is composed of six [[Register (sculpture)|registers]], with gods, beings (a [[Scorpion man]] for example), etc. The recto contains [[Cuneiform script|cuneiform]] text, relating the military services of Šitti-Marduk.
