{{Infobox aircraft occurrence |name = Sudan Airways Flight 109 |occurrence_type = Accident |image = Sudan Airways A310-300 ST-ATN DXB 2008-4-11.png |image_size = 250 |alt = |caption = The aircraft involved in the accident is seen here on approach to [[Dubai International Airport]] in {{start date|df=yes|2008|4}} |date = 10 June 2008 |type = Runway overrun |site = [[Khartoum International Airport]] |coordinates = {{coord|15|35|22|N|32|33|11|E|type:event_source:kolossus-plwiki|display=inline,title}} |aircraft_type = [[Airbus A310-300]] |aircraft_name = |operator = [[Sudan Airways]] |tail_number = ST-ATN |origin = [[Queen Alia International Airport]] |stopover = [[Damascus International Airport]] |stopover0 = |stopover1 = |stopover2 = |stopover3 = |last_stopover = [[Port Sudan New International Airport]] |destination = Khartoum International Airport |passengers = 203 |crew = 11 |injuries = |fatalities = 30 |survivors = 184 }}
'''Sudan Airways Flight 109''' was an international scheduled [[Amman]]–[[Damascus]]–[[Khartoum]] passenger service, operated with an [[Airbus A310]], that crashed on landing at [[Khartoum International Airport]] on 10 June 2008, approximately at 17:00 [[UTC]], killing 30 of 214 occupants on board.<ref name="ASN">{{ASN accident|id= 20080610-0|accessdate= 5 June 2012}}</ref><ref name="Dozens killed in Sudan air crash" /><ref name="CNN">{{cite news|url= http://www.cnn.com/2008/WORLD/africa/06/10/sudan.plane/index.html|title= Passenger plane crashes in flames in Sudan|accessdate= 10 June 2008|work= [[CNN]] |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20080611022323/http://www.cnn.com/2008/WORLD/africa/06/10/sudan.plane/index.html|archivedate= 11 June 2008}}</ref>
==Aircraft== The aircraft involved in the accident was an [[Airbus A310-300|Airbus A310-324]], [[Serial number|c/n]] 548, [[Aircraft registration|tail number]] {{Airreg|ST|ATN|,}} that had its maiden flight on 23 August 1990 as F-WWCV.<ref name="Airfleets">{{cite web|title= Airbus A310 MSN 548|url= http://www.airfleets.net/ficheapp/plane-a310-548.htm|work= AirFleets.net|accessdate= 25 January 2012}}</ref> Equipped with a twin-[[Pratt & Whitney PW4000|PW4152]] powerplant, it was delivered new to [[Singapore Airlines]] on 22 October 1990 and [[Aircraft registration|register]]ed 9V-STU.<ref name="Airfleets"/><ref>{{cite web|title= Accident information : Airbus A310 Sudan Airways ST-ATN|url= http://www.airfleets.net/crash/crash_report_SudanAirways_ST-ATN.htm|work= Airfleets.net|accessdate= 25 January 2012}}</ref> Re-registered VT-EVF, it was delivered to [[Air India]] on 10 March 2001.<ref name="Airfleets"/> The aircraft was finally registered ST-ATN, and delivered to [[Sudan Airways]] on 1 December 2007.<ref name="Airfleets"/> According to [[Airbus]], it had accumulated 52,000 flight hours and 21,000 cycles.<ref name="Sudan A310 veered off runway during landing" />
==Description== The flight originated in Amman and had its final destination in Khartoum with an intermediate stop in Damascus. The presence of a sandstorm and heavy rain prevented the aircraft to land at Khartoum and forced it to be diverted to [[Port Sudan]]. The aircraft was later allowed to fly back to its original destination.<ref name="Dozens die in Sudan jet inferno" /> The flight landed at Khartoum Airport at 17:26&nbsp;UTC, but was not able to stop within the paved area. Following the aircraft overrunning the runway and coming to rest {{convert|215|m}} beyond the end of runway 36 a fire erupted on the starboard side.<ref name="Final report" />{{rp|8}} The slides on the side the fire started at could not be deployed; people on board evacuated the aircraft using the port side slides.<ref name="Final report" />{{rp|9}}
==Cause== The runway overrun was caused by a combination of a long landing flare, the wet runway, landing without autobrake selected on, and one engine thrust reverser that was deactivated.<ref name="Final report" />{{rp|39}} The aircraft had been dispatched with the port engine thrust reverser deactivated. This condition caused it to veer to the right when the captain activated reverse thrust in both engines in order to stop the aircraft within {{convert|2080|m}} of runway left.<ref name="Fatal Sudan A310 overrun crew unaware of tailwind" /> Reports indicated the occurrence of a big sandstorm at Khartoum earlier that day that was followed by low visibility and heavy rain and winds at the time of the accident.<ref name="14 still missing after air crash blaze" /> Contributing to the long landing flare was that the crew had been incorrectly informed that they had a {{convert|7|kn|adj=on}} headwind for landing when they actually had a {{convert|15|kn|adj=on}} tailwind.<ref name="Final report" />{{rp|39}}
==Casualties== Out of {{cardinal|203}} passengers and {{cardinal|11}} crew members on board the aircraft,<ref name="Final report" />{{rp|8}} {{cardinal|29}} passengers and {{cardinal to word|1}} crew member lost their lives.<ref name="Final report" />{{rp|9}} Many of the casualties were children with disabilities and seniors returning from treatment in Amman.<ref>{{cite news|title=Sudan Airways Airbus crashes at Khartoum airport|url=http://www.sudantribune.com/Sudan-Airway-Airbus-crashes-at,27473|publisher=[[Sudan Tribune]]|date=10 June 2008|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/68qHch2Lv?url=http://www.sudantribune.com/Sudan-Airway-Airbus-crashes-at,27473|archivedate=1 July 2012|accessdate=11 September 2012|deadurl=yes|df=dmy-all}}</ref>
===Notable passengers=== [[Abbas al-Fadini]] (Member of the [[Parliament of Sudan]]) was on board the flight and survived unscathed.<ref name=Times>{{cite news | url = http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/world/africa/article4110607.ece| publisher = The Times| title = At least 28 die in Sudan air crash disaster| accessdate = 11 June 2008 | location=London | date=11 June 2008}}{{subscription required}}</ref>
